Project Objective

The primary goal of this Jupyter notebook is to analyze heart failure data to identify key trends and observations. By understanding these patterns, we aim to better predict when a patient is at an increased risk of mortality due to a heart failure.

Data Features

The dataset includes the following features:

  • Age
  • Anaemia
  • Creatinine Phosphokinase
  • Diabetes
  • Ejection Fraction
  • High Blood Pressure
  • Platelets
  • Serum Creatinine
  • Serum Sodium
  • Sex
  • Smoking
  • Time

Model Development

Using the above features, the objective is to develop a predictive model that can accurately determine whether a death event has occurred due to a heart failure.

Observing the groups, it seems as if many of the features are significantly different for the group of people who have died versus those who are still alive. Therefore, I now want to perform significance testing to see if my hypothesis holds true.

In[]:
results = {}
for column in df.columns[:-1]: 
    t_stat, p_val = stats.ttest_1samp(death_event[column], df[column].mean())
    results[column] = (t_stat, p_val)

for feature, (t_stat, p_val) in results.items():
    print(f"{feature}: t-statistic = {t_stat:.3f}, p-value = {p_val:.3f}")

age: t-statistic = 13.028, p-value = 0.000

Features like age, anaemia, creatinine phosphokinase, ejection fraction, high blood pressure, serum creatinine, serum sodium, and time show significant differences, meaning that these factors are notably different in patients who died compared to the overall sample. In contrast, features like diabetes, platelets, and smoking do not show a statistically significant difference.

Also two most significant of these features being time and ejection_fraction both show a negative relationship between DEATH_EVENT.

I want to now see if creating my own feature by summing the results of whether a patient has high blood pressure, diabetes, and smoking is predictive of death.

However, generally speaking, having a higher combination of these risk factors makes you more likely to die, although this findings could be due to a small sample size especially with group four.

Model Builing

Here is a simple LogisticRegression model that uses all the factors given to predict if a DEATH_EVENT has occured

In[]:
X= df[['age', 'anaemia', 'creatinine_phosphokinase', 'diabetes',
       'ejection_fraction', 'high_blood_pressure', 'platelets',
       'serum_creatinine', 'serum_sodium', 'sex', 'smoking', 'time','risk_val']]
Y =df['DEATH_EVENT']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,Y,test_size=0.33, random_state=42)
In[]:
logisticRegr = LogisticRegression(max_iter=10000)
In[]:
logisticRegr.fit(X_train,y_train)
logisticRegr.score(X_test,y_test)
y_pred=logisticRegr.predict(X_test)
cross_val_score(logisticRegr,X_test,y_test,cv=5)
Out[]:
array([0.84242424, 0.82424242, 0.81818182, 0.82121212, 0.85151515])

Using cross-validation, we can see that the general accuracy is around 80%, which is not bad. However, I want to better understand why the model is failing, so I'm going to take a look at the types of predictions it's getting wrong by looking at both the Recall and Precision of the model.

In[]:
print("Accuracy:",metrics.accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred))
print("Recall:",metrics.recall_score(y_test,y_pred))
print("Precision:",metrics.precision_score(y_test,y_pred))

Accuracy: 0.8242424242424242
Recall: 0.6607495069033531
Precision: 0.739514348785872

Instead we are now going to try using a gradient boosting model to see if we can learn how to predict wheather a death event has occured.

In[]:
bstmodel=XGBClassifier(n_estimators=5, max_depth=5, learning_rate=1, objective='binary:logistic')

bstmodel.fit(X_train,y_train)
y_pred=bstmodel.predict(X_test)
print("Accuracy:",metrics.accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred))
print("Recall:",metrics.recall_score(y_test,y_pred))
print("Precision:",metrics.precision_score(y_test,y_pred))

Accuracy: 0.9775757575757575
Recall: 0.9684418145956607
Precision: 0.958984375

Now we have created a model with nearly perfect prediction accuracy on whether a death event has occurred.I want to observe both the feature importances and decision tree to best understand how the model does so well.

Reviewing the data generated by our model allows us to draw several conclusions and formulate numerous hypotheses about the critical factors in determining when someone is at risk of death. A primary and obvious indicator, as shown through charts, decision trees, correlations, and the model itself, is the role that the timing until the next appointment plays in predicting heart failure death. What remains a mystery, however, is exactly why this is the case. Could it be that the frequency of appointments, High frequency means that the patients have short times which is likely due to their poor conditions so it would make sense that it close to their time in general.Suggesting that being given a short time to return is an indication of death being imminent?At the same time you give someone a long enough time come back though and eventually they die so could it be the case that many patient are not getting check up regularly enough and they just die close to the appointment days.Whatever the case is it is clear thier is alot more that goes into understanding time until appointments relationship whith the death event.Another interesting aspects is seeing the discrepancy between the importance of diabetes in the model has opposed to looking at the correlation and hypothesis testing which give the indications that it woul not be as important as the other factors.smoking similar had outcomes on correlation and hypothesis testing and yet it was not as helpful in the model as diabetes.In the future I would love to have more data and information on some of the feature as think it's not accurate to categorize all smokers identically because there is a significant difference between smoking once a day and smoking five times a day. Differentiating between levels of smoking frequency can provide more precise insights into associated health risks and behaviors.
